[
  {
    "title": "Fractions, Percentages, and Indices",
    "objective": "Apply fractions, percentages, and indices to electrical values.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In electrical work, we often deal with percentages and indices to express values accurately. A percentage represents a part of 100. To use a percentage in a calculation, you must convert it to a decimal by dividing by 100. For example, 5% becomes 0.05. If you multiply a value by 5 instead of 0.05, your result will be 100 times too large, leading to dangerous errors in circuit design.",
      "Indices are small numbers, or powers, that tell you how many times to multiply a base number by itself. In this trade, we use 'powers of ten' as shorthand for metric prefixes. The prefix 'kilo' (k) means 1,000, which is written as 10³ (10 × 10 × 10). The prefix 'milli' (m) means 0.001, written as 10⁻³. Using indices allows us to handle very large or very small numbers, such as 230,000 Volts or 0.005 Amps, without writing out long strings of zeros."
    ],
    "hint": "Remember to divide a percentage by 100 before calculating, and treat 10³ as 1,000."
  },
  {
    "title": "Algebra and Transposition",
    "objective": "Transpose simple linear equations to isolate a specific variable.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Algebra allows us to find an unknown value using a formula. Transposition is the process of rearranging a formula to isolate the specific variable you need to find. The golden rule of transposition is: 'change the side, change the operation.' This means if a value is being multiplied on one side of the equals sign, it must be divided when moved to the other side.",
      "Consider Ohm’s Law: V = I × R, where V is Voltage, I is Current, and R is Resistance. If you know the Voltage and Resistance but need to find the Current (I), you must move the R to the other side. Since R is currently multiplying I, it moves to the other side as a divisor. This results in the transposed formula: I = V / R. By performing the inverse operation, you maintain the balance of the equation while isolating your target value."
    ],
    "hint": "If a value is multiplying on one side, it must divide on the other side of the equals sign."
  },
  {
    "title": "Trigonometry and Triangles",
    "objective": "Use Pythagoras’ Theorem and basic trigonometry (SOH CAH TOA) for right-angled triangles.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Electrical calculations for Alternating Current (AC) often use right-angled triangles to represent the relationship between different types of power or resistance. Pythagoras’ Theorem (a² + b² = c²) is used to find the length of a missing side. In this formula, 'c' is always the hypotenuse, which is the longest side opposite the 90-degree right angle. It is vital to remember that Pythagoras only works on triangles that contain a right angle.",
      "To find angles or sides when only one side and an angle are known, we use Trigonometry, specifically the SOH CAH TOA ratios. SOH stands for Sine = Opposite / Hypotenuse; CAH stands for Cosine = Adjacent / Hypotenuse; and TOA stands for Tangent = Opposite / Adjacent. These ratios link the lengths of the sides to the size of the internal angles, which is the foundation for calculating the 'phase angle' in complex AC circuits."
    ],
    "hint": "Pythagoras finds side lengths (a² + b² = c²), while SOH CAH TOA links angles to side ratios."
  },
  {
    "title": "Statistics in Electrical Work",
    "objective": "Identify and calculate mean, median, and mode from a set of electrical data.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Statistics help electricians analyze sets of test results to ensure an installation is safe and consistent. The most common tool is the 'Mean,' which is the mathematical average. To find the mean, you add all the values in a set together and divide the total by the number of values. For instance, if you take three earth electrode readings, you average them to get a reliable final result.",
      "The 'Median' is the middle value when all readings are listed in order from smallest to largest. If there is an even number of readings, the median is the average of the two middle numbers. The 'Mode' is simply the value that appears most frequently in your data set. While the mean and median are often similar, they are distinct; the mean accounts for every value, whereas the median identifies the central point, helping you spot if one specific reading is an unusual 'outlier' that might indicate a fault."
    ],
    "hint": "The mean is the total divided by the count; the median is the middle number in a sorted list."
  }
]

